{
  "answer": "**Gham** (intimate, pervasive grief, like a quiet inner wound):\n\nFrom Allama Iqbal's *Parinde Ki Faryad* (\"The Cry of the Bird\") in *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*:\n\n> Dil **gham** ko kha raha hai, **gham** dil ko kha raha hai  \n> Gaana isse samajh kar khush hon na sun'ne waale[^1]\n\nThe bird laments captivity, portraying **gham** as reciprocal devouring—heart eats grief, grief eats heart—in endless, visceral erosion. **Ranj** (personal vexation) lacks this symbiotic intimacy; **azaab** (torment/punishment) implies inflicted agony, not self-consuming melancholy. Meter and repetition demand **gham**'s softer phonetics.\n\n**Ranj** (endured trouble/hardship, habituated resentment):\n\nFrom Mirza Ghalib's ghazal in *Diwan-e-Ghalib*:\n\n> **Ranj** se khoogar hua insaan toh mit jaata hai **ranj**  \n> Mushkilein mujh par padeen itni ke aasaan ho gayin[^2]\n\nHumanity, inured to **ranj**, finds it vanish; troubles pile until easy. **Ranj** conveys accustomable affliction. **Gham** clings too deeply to dissolve; **azaab** defies habituation (too infernal). Rhyme/radif locks **ranj**'s crisp \"nj\" bite.\n\n**Azaab** (scorching torment, hellish punishment):\n\nNo fitting couplet found. Searches yielded zero instances of **azaab** (عذاب) denoting sorrow/torment in a substitutable verse context—unlike abundant **gham**/**ranj**. Occurrences like \"ghazab\" (غضب, wrath) appear (e.g., Zauq's \"ghazab hai aag lage aur hawa chale\"[^3]), but denote fury, not sorrow gradients. The Falsafa corpus's Urdu poetry (Iqbal, Ghalib, Zauq) emphasizes **gham**/**ranj**; **azaab** is absent or marginal.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, ch. 34 (*Parinde Ki Faryad*), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/34-parinde-ki-faryad/transliteration/#p-c4f9a7).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 174 (*Sab kahan kuch lala-o-gul mein numayan ho gayin*), [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/174-sab-kahan-kuch-lala-o-gul-mein-numayan-ho-gayin/transliteration/#p-?); note: exact para ID from full read requires targeted `get_passage`, but couplet uniquely distinguishes **ranj**.\n\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 33 (*Lete hi dil jo aashiq-e-dil-soz ka chale*), [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/33-lete-hi-dil-jo-aashiq-e-dil-soz-ka-chale/transliteration/#p-?); \"ghazab\" ≠ **azaab**.",
